============================================================
HTML BASICS – FOUNDATION FOR JAVASCRIPT INTERACTIONS
============================================================

1. HTML DOCUMENT STRUCTURE
------------------------------------------------------------
<!DOCTYPE html>          → Defines document type as HTML5
<html>                   → Root element
<head>                   → Metadata: title, links, scripts, etc.
  <title>Page Title</title> → Title shown in browser tab
</head>
<body>                   → Visible content of the page
  <!-- Your content here -->
</body>
</html>

Goal: JS usually manipulates elements inside <body>.

------------------------------------------------------------
2. HEADINGS & PARAGRAPHS
------------------------------------------------------------
<h1> to <h6> → Headings, h1 = biggest, h6 = smallest
<p>         → Paragraph

Example:
<h1>My Page</h1>
<p>Welcome to my webpage!</p>

Goal: JS can change text, e.g., document.getElementById('id').innerText

------------------------------------------------------------
3. LINKS & IMAGES
------------------------------------------------------------
<a href="https://example.com">Link Text</a>   → Hyperlink
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Description">       → Image

Goal: JS can change href/src dynamically
Example: document.querySelector('a').href = 'https://google.com';

------------------------------------------------------------
4. LISTS
------------------------------------------------------------
Unordered list: <ul> with <li>
Ordered list: <ol> with <li>

Example:
<ul>
  <li>Apple</li>
  <li>Banana</li>
</ul>

Goal: JS can add/remove list items dynamically

------------------------------------------------------------
5. DIV & SPAN
------------------------------------------------------------
<div> → Block container (group elements)
<span> → Inline container (small content)

Example:
<div id="container">
  <span>Hello</span>
</div>

Goal: JS selects containers to modify content/style

------------------------------------------------------------
6. FORMS & INPUT ELEMENTS
------------------------------------------------------------
<form> → Form container
<input type="text">        → Text input
<input type="button" value="Click Me"> → Button
<input type="checkbox">    → Checkbox
<input type="radio">       → Radio button
<textarea></textarea>      → Multi-line input

Goal: JS reads/writes values with .value and handles events
Example:
let name = document.getElementById('nameInput').value;

------------------------------------------------------------
7. BUTTONS
------------------------------------------------------------
<button id="myBtn">Click Me</button>

Goal: JS detects clicks and performs actions
Example:
document.getElementById('myBtn').addEventListener('click', function(){
  alert('Button clicked!');
});

------------------------------------------------------------
8. SCRIPT TAGS (LINKING JS)
------------------------------------------------------------
Inline JS:
<script>
  alert('Hello World');
</script>

External JS:
<script src="app.js"></script>

Goal: Use JS to manipulate HTML elements

------------------------------------------------------------
9. HTML ATTRIBUTES IMPORTANT FOR JS
------------------------------------------------------------
id      → Unique identifier (getElementById)
class   → Group elements (querySelector/querySelectorAll)
name    → Forms
value   → Input value
src     → Image source
href    → Link destination

Example:
<input type="text" id="username" value="Ajay">
JS: document.getElementById('username').value → "Ajay"

------------------------------------------------------------
10. COMMENTS
------------------------------------------------------------
<!-- This is an HTML comment -->

Goal: JS can create/change comments; mainly for readability

------------------------------------------------------------
11. EXAMPLE – COMBINING ALL TAGS
------------------------------------------------------------
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>JS Interaction Example</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1 id="mainHeading">Welcome!</h1>
<p id="intro">This is a sample page.</p>

<a href="https://example.com" id="link">Go to Example</a>
<img src="logo.png" alt="Logo" id="logo">

<ul id="fruitsList">
  <li>Apple</li>
  <li>Banana</li>
</ul>

<div id="container">
  <span>Inline text</span>
</div>

<form id="userForm">
  <input type="text" id="nameInput" value="Ajay">
  <input type="button" id="submitBtn" value="Submit">
</form>

<script>
  // Change heading text
  document.getElementById('mainHeading').innerText = "Hello, JS!";

  // Read input value
  let username = document.getElementById('nameInput').value;
  console.log("User:", username);

  // Add new list item dynamically
  let ul = document.getElementById('fruitsList');
  let li = document.createElement('li');
  li.innerText = 'Mango';
  ul.appendChild(li);

  // Handle button click
  document.getElementById('submitBtn').addEventListener('click', function(){
    alert('Submitted: ' + document.getElementById('nameInput').value);
  });

  // Change link dynamically
  document.getElementById('link').href = 'https://google.com';
  document.getElementById('link').innerText = 'Go to Google';
</script>

</body>
</html>

------------------------------------------------------------
SUMMARY – WHAT YOU NEED FOR JAVASCRIPT
------------------------------------------------------------
1. Select elements: getElementById, querySelector
2. Read/write content: innerText, innerHTML, value
3. Respond to events: click, input, submit
4. Understand attributes: id, class, value, src, href
5. Create dynamic elements: JS can add/remove <li>, <div>, <img>, etc.

Goal achieved: Ready to interact with HTML using JavaScript.
============================================================
